# gitban-provided sample — merge the WHOLE gitban-managed section below into your
# .gitignore (do not cherry-pick lines: the negation chain is interdependent).
# Refreshed on every gitban update.
#
# Non-gitban repo (you do NOT track your .gitban/ PM surface)? Ignore the whole tree
# with a single line instead of the allowlist below:
#   .gitban/**
# === gitban-managed: version-control allowlist ===
# Ignore all gitban working state by default; track only the
# project-management surface (roadmap, cards) and the dispatch state
# the harness reads to resume idempotently (agent inboxes). Everything
# else — telemetry, machine-local identity, regenerable artifacts — is
# ignored so new artifact classes are private by default.
.gitban/**
!.gitban/roadmap/
!.gitban/roadmap/**
!.gitban/cards/
!.gitban/cards/**
# Agent inboxes carry dispatch state (the dispatch-log + the -ERROR.md
# status files a crashed agent writes back) plus review provenance, and
# must survive a fresh clone so a resuming dispatcher does not re-run
# completed work. Re-including them requires un-ignoring each parent dir
# first; the negations stop before traces/ and logs/, which stay ignored.
!.gitban/agents/
!.gitban/agents/*/
!.gitban/agents/*/inbox/
!.gitban/agents/*/inbox/**
# Harness hooks are tracked: they are load-bearing PreToolUse guards that
# every checkout needs to operate the dispatch harness, and — unlike
# templates — they are NOT lazily regenerated. Git worktrees and fresh
# clones receive only tracked files, and the MCP deploys hooks to the main
# workspace only, never into a worktree; untracking them breaks worktree
# dispatch and deletes them from a teammate's disk on pull. So they stay
# tracked. (lib/ is under hooks/ and is covered by the recursive negation.)
!.gitban/hooks/
!.gitban/hooks/**
# Legacy throwaway card artifacts: the cards/** negation above would
# otherwise re-include these scratch copies. Keep them ignored.
.gitban/cards/**/*_temp_*
.gitban/cards/**/*_backup_*
